        <a class="anchor" id="babilong-niah-reasoning"></a>
        <h2 class="title is-4">
          Needle-in-a-Haystack: Reasoning over Relevant Facts
        </h2>
        <div class="content has-text-justified">
          <p>
            We evaluate <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> on <a
              href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.10149"
              target="_blank">BabiLong</a
            >, which hides critical facts ("needles") within thousands of tokens
            of irrelevant text ("haystack"), then requires finding and reasoning
            over those facts. We test three difficulty levels: single-hop (QA1),
            two-hop (QA2), and three-hop (QA3) reasoning.
          </p>
          <p>
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> outperforms all baselines across all
            reasoning depths, including much larger models and specialized long-context
            models supporting 512K–1M tokens.
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> (Qwen-7B) achieves higher accuracy than
            FT-ICR (Qwen-7B) at 8K contexts, and when extrapolating to 32K contexts,
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> outperforms FT-ICR by 23 percentage
            points on average.
          </p>
        </div>

        <a class="anchor" id="multi-doc-qa"></a>
        <h2 class="title is-4">Multi-Document Question Answering</h2>
        <div class="content has-text-justified">
          <p>
            On <a href="https://hotpotqa.github.io/" target="_blank">HotpotQA</a
            > and <a
              href="https://nlp.cs.washington.edu/triviaqa/"
              target="_blank">TriviaQA</a
            >, which require retrieving and reasoning across multiple documents,
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> (trained on 8K tokens) beats FT-ICR
            by 15–20% depending on model size. When generalizing to 32K-token contexts
            unseen during training, <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> maintains a
            14–30% advantage.
          </p>
          <p>
            Compared to specialized long-context models like <a
              href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.15383"
              target="_blank">Qwen-1M</a
            >
            and <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.02660" target="_blank"
              >ProLong-512K</a
            >,
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> matches their performance with
            far less specialized training. While GPT-4.1 and Gemini-1.5-pro still
            lead, <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> significantly closes the gap.
          </p>
        </div>

        <a class="anchor" id="drop-in-ocean-reasoning"></a>
        <h2 class="title is-4">
          Drops-in-an-Ocean: Stress-Testing with Similar Distractors
        </h2>
        <div class="content has-text-justified">
          <p>
            Standard NIAH datasets have a fundamental limitation: target
            information often differs stylistically from surrounding text,
            making retrieval artificially easy. We propose <strong
              >Drops-in-the-Ocean</strong
            > (DIO), which forms long contexts from structurally similar documents.

            Our synthetic <strong>Student Records</strong> dataset simulates a database
            with evaluation tasks of increasing complexity: (1) <strong
              >Recall</strong
            > (retrieve attributes for a student ID), (2) <strong
              >Relation</strong
            > (compare attributes between two IDs), and (3) <strong
              >Aggregate</strong
            > (max, min, and average grades).
          </p>
          <p>
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> outperforms FT-ICR across all task difficulties
            and context lengths, with a smaller performance drop at 32K tokens. The
            performance gap widens monotonically with task difficulty, suggesting
            <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> enhances complex reasoning rather than
            merely improving retrieval. Both <span class="dmethod">PERK</span> variants
            outperform specialized long-context models, and <span
              class="dmethod">PERK</span
            > (Qwen-7B) matches or exceeds commercial models even on Aggregate tasks.
          </p>
        </div>

